croStrategy</h2> </td> </tr> </table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=
=80=99s the basic idea of convertible arbitrage. You buy a convertible bond=
 that will pay you back, in a year, either (1) $1,000 in cash or (2) 20 sha=
res of the company=E2=80=99s stock. (Or some other =E2=80=9Cconversion rati=
o=E2=80=9D; 20 is an arbitrary simple number.) If the stock today is at, sa=
y, $2 per share, then those 20 shares of stock are worth $40, and you will =
almost definitely want the $1,000 in a year. If the stock today is at $200 =
per share, then those 20 shares of stock are worth $4,000, and you will alm=
ost definitely want the stock in a year. At very high stock prices, the con=
vertible bond is essentially equivalent to stock; at very low stock prices,=
 it is essentially equivalent to a $1,000 bond.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">You, as a convertible arbitrageur, are in the business of hedging your=
 stock-price risk. You do this by selling the stock short. How much you sel=
l short depends on how much stock-price risk you have. If the stock price i=
s very high, then the convertible bond is essentially stock, and a $1 move =
in the stock price should cause about a $20 move in the convertible price (=
because the convertible represents 20 shares). So you sell short 20 shares =
of stock to hedge your stock price risk. If the stock price is very low, th=
en the convertible has essentially no exposure to the stock, and a $1 move =
in the stock price should cause about a $0 move in the convertible price. S=
o you sell short zero shares of stock to hedge your (non-existent) stock pr=
ice risk.<a href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">And in between those extremes, the convertible has some medium amoun=
t of stock exposure. If the stock today is at $40 per share, then the conve=
rtible might have, say, a 70% exposure to the stock: A $1 move in the stock=
 price should cause about a $14 move in the convertible price ($1 times 20 =
shares times 70%). So you=E2=80=99d sell short 14 shares of stock =E2=80=94=
=C2=A070% of the shares underlying the convertible =E2=80=94=C2=A0to hedge =
your stock price risk. The actual number =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Chedge =
ratio=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cdelta=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0varies smoothly be=
tween 0% and 100% and can be calculated by reasonably well-understood metho=
ds. The point is that eventually, at maturity, the convertible will be paid=
 back in cash or stock, so eventually it will be pure cash or pure stock; b=
efore that, the convertible has some varying probability of being cash or s=
tock.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does it mean to hedge your stock=
-price risk=3F Well, literally, it means that if the stock moves up (or dow=
n) by $1, you will make (or lose) some money on your convertible bond, and =
you will lose (or make) some offsetting amount of money on your stock posit=
ion.<a href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a> The stock can go up or down, a=
nd you don=E2=80=99t care; you=E2=80=99re hedged either way.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">You can=E2=80=99t just set this and forget it, though. Th=
e higher the stock price is, the more stock-like the convertible is: If the=
 stock price is high, the convertible is mostly stock, but if it is low, th=
e convertible is mostly a regular bond. So your correct hedge ratio will ch=
ange as the stock moves up or down. So if the stock goes up by $1, you will=
 make some money on your convertible and lose some offsetting amount of mon=
ey on your stock hedge, but then at the end of the day you will=C2=A0<em>ad=
just=C2=A0</em>your hedge by selling more stock, because the convertible no=
w has more stock exposure. On the other hand, if the stock goes down by $1,=
 the convertible will become less stock-like, so you will have to adjust yo=
ur hedge by buying back some of the stock you were short.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">This is the more practical meaning of hedging your stock-pri=
ce risk. It means that every day the stock moves around and you rebalance y=
our hedge.=C2=A0When the stock goes up, you sell some stock at high prices.=
 When the stock goes down, you buy some stock at low prices. Hedging the co=
nvertible means buying stock low and selling it high.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The thing to realize is that, the more you get to do this, the m=
ore money you make. If the stock goes up one day and down the next, you sel=
l stock on the up day and buy it back on the down day and make a profit. If=
 the stock just stays flat or drifts up or down, you don=E2=80=99t make tha=
t much money adjusting your hedge; if the stock bounces around wildly, you =
do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So a convertible bond is a bet on volat=
ility: The more the company=E2=80=99s stock bounces around, the more money =
convertible arbitrageurs can make.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I used t=
o be a convertible bond investment banker, and this was, often, roughly the=
 pitch to companies: =E2=80=9CYou have a valuable asset that you don=E2=80=
=99t even know about: volatility. Your stock is volatile. You probably don=
=E2=80=99t think about that much, and if you do, you think it=E2=80=99s bad=
. You don=E2=80=99t like your volatile stock. But do you know who does=3F =
Convertible arbitrageurs. They will pay you a lot of money for that volatil=
ity, in the form of cheap convertible bond financing.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
